gland, United Kingdom","Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England":"Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, including Stanford (Bedfordshire, Kent), Stanford Dingley and Stanford in the Vale (Berkshire), Stanford le Hope and Stanford Rivers (Essex), Stanford Bishop and Stanford Regis (Herefordshire), Stanford on Avon (Northamptonshire), Stanford on Soar (Nottinghamshire), and Stanford on Teme (Worcestershire); also from Stamford (Lincolnshire, Northumberland), Stamford Bridge (East Yorkshire), and Standford in Headley (Hampshire), all of which appear as <i>Stanford</i> in medieval documents. The placenames all derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. This surname has been established in Ireland since the 16th century, where it is also found under the variant <i>Stankard</i>.","History: An early bearer of this surname in North America, Thomas Stanford of England, settled in Charlestown, MA, in the mid 17th century and started a family line that includes Leland Stanford (1824–93), the railroad developer who was governor of CA, a US senator, and the founding benefactor of Stanford University."],"variants":[{"name":"Stanforth","meanings":["English:","mainly a variant of   Stanford  , which may have migrated to North Yorkshire and Northumberland from Norfolk and Suffolk by the North Sea coastal trade.","variant of   Staniforth  ."]},{"name":"Standford","meanings":["English: variant, with intrusive -d-, of   Stanford  . Compare   Standiford  ."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":12,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":43,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":68,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":81,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jocosa Joyce Stanford was born in 1247, in Leighton, Shropshire, England, her father, Hugh Sanford, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Hugh Sanford, was 22. She married William Jenkinus Leighton in 1267, in Leeds, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in Leighton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1247–":"1247–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1243–Male":"1243–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1274–Male":"1274–Surnud","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","about 1272":"umbes 1272","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1272":"1272","abt 1299":"umbes 1274","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1267":"1267","1221":"1221","1243":"1243","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Leeds, West Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England":"Thornton Mayow, Cheshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Leeds, Yorkshire, England":"Leeds, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1247–":"1247–Kuollut","1247–Female":"1247–Kuollut","1243–Male":"1243–Kuollut","1272–Female":"1272–Kuollut","1274–Male":"1274–Kuollut","1275–Male":"1275–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1221–Male":"1221–Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","about 1272":"noin 1272","about 1280":"noin 1280","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1272":"1272","abt 1299":"noin 1274","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1267":"1267","1221":"1221","1243":"1243","1328":"132